{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480102"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:37:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:37:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582379"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:40:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:40:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.69,0.15,0.07,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75436"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60946"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"92"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"10886"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"863"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1458"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43775"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75436"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for review of hepatitis B infection diagnosed six months ago. He initially presented with a one-month history of fever, malaise, jaundice, fatigue, poor appetite and nausea. He now reports feeling better with resolution of jaundice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His risk factors include sharing needles for intravenous drug use and unprotected sexual intercourse with a male partner. He has never received hepatitis B vaccination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Clinical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following tests would best determine if he has ongoing hepatitis B infection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Liver function tests","Hepatitis B Surface Antigen (HBsAg)","Hepatitis B Core Antibody (Anti-HBc)","Hepatitis B Surface Antibody (Anti-HBs)","Hepatitis B DNA"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents for follow-up of hepatitis B infection. Understanding the serological markers is crucial for determining disease status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B Surface Antigen (HBsAg)\u003C/strong\u003E is the most reliable marker for detecting current hepatitis B infection. It appears early in infection and its persistence beyond six months defines chronic infection. This makes it the ideal test to determine if infection is ongoing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-HBc\u003C/strong\u003E appears at symptom onset and remains present for life in both resolved and chronic infections. While it confirms exposure, it cannot distinguish between current and past infection without additional markers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-HBs\u003C/strong\u003E indicates immunity, either from vaccination or recovery from natural infection. Its presence in isolation suggests resolved infection or successful vaccination, but does not help determine if infection is ongoing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B DNA\u003C/strong\u003E testing quantifies viral load and is useful for monitoring disease activity and treatment response, but is not the primary test for determining infection status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver function tests\u003C/strong\u003E may show hepatocellular injury but are non-specific and cannot confirm ongoing viral infection. They may be normal or abnormal in both acute and chronic hepatitis B.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hepatitis B Surface Antigen (HBsAg) is the key marker for detecting current hepatitis B infection","Persistence of HBsAg beyond six months defines chronic hepatitis B infection","Risk factors for hepatitis B infection include intravenous drug use and unprotected sexual contact"],"references":["Hepatitis B. In: World Health Organisation [online]. 2021 [cited 2 February 2021]. Available at: https://www.who.int/en/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/hepatitis-b","Wilkins T, Sams R, Carpenter M. Hepatitis B: Screening, Prevention, Diagnosis, and Treatment. Am Fam Physician. 2019 Mar 1;99(5):314-323. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/afp/2019/0301/p314.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":